
	<sn><md>## Mass of the Atmosphere{.fg-red .text-center}

The atmosphere, though appearing light and invisible, `has a measurable mass` that plays a vital role in Earth’s climate, weather, and life-supporting systems. The mass of the atmosphere refers to the `total weight of all the gases surrounding Earth`, held in place by gravity. This mass not only ==creates atmospheric pressure== at the surface but also helps regulate temperature, protects from harmful radiation, and supports life.


The estimated total mass of Earth’s atmosphere is about `5.15 × 10¹⁸ kilograms`. While this seems extremely large, it is small compared to the total mass of Earth, which is about `5.97 × 10²⁴ kilograms`. This means the atmosphere makes up only about ==one-millionth of Earth’s total mass==.
