<sn><md>## Calculating{.fg-red .text-center}


Using the physics relations:

* $p = \dfrac{F}{A}$  (pressure = force/area)
* $F = mg$  (weight = mass × gravity)

Combine them:

$$
p = \frac{mg}{A} \;\Rightarrow\; m = \frac{pA}{g}
$$

#### Step 1: Use standard values{.text-end}

* Sea-level standard pressure: $p = 101{,}325\ \text{Pa}$
* Mean gravitational acceleration: $g = 9.80665\ \text{m s}^{-2}$
* Earth’s surface area: $A = 4\pi R^2$, with $R \approx 6.371\times10^6\ \text{m}$

Compute $A$:

$$
A = 4\pi (6.371\times10^6)^2 \approx 5.1006\times10^{14}\ \text{m}^2
$$

#### Step 2: Atmospheric **mass** {.text-end}

$$
m = \frac{pA}{g} \approx \frac{(101{,}325)\times(5.1006\times10^{14})}{9.80665}
\approx 5.27\times10^{18}\ \text{kg}
$$

#### Step 3: Atmospheric **weight** (force){.text-end}

$$
F = pA \approx (101{,}325)\times(5.1006\times10^{14})
\approx 5.17\times10^{19}\ \text{N}
$$

#### Helpful checkpoint (per-unit-area view){.text-end}

Mass of air above 1 m² at sea level:

$$
\frac{m}{A}=\frac{p}{g}\approx \frac{101{,}325}{9.80665}\approx 1.0332\times10^{4}\ \text{kg/m}^2
$$

---

**Notes:** The computed mass $\sim 5.27\times10^{18}\ \text{kg}$ is close to commonly cited estimates (\~$5.15\times10^{18}\ \text{kg}$). Differences arise because the calculation assumes uniform sea-level pressure and average $g$, while the real atmosphere varies with altitude, temperature, and weather.{bar}
